Poly (2-tert-butylaminoethyl) methacrylate, PTBAEMA (Fig. 8.1
), is a typical representative water-insoluble biocide which can be blended with polyolefins
to provide surface modification (Seyfriedsberger et al., 2006) (Table 8.2
). The major role of PTBAEMA is believed to be the displacement of Ca2+ and/or Mg2+ ions from the outer membrane of the bacteria, which is accordingly disorganized and finally disrupted.

N-halamine antimicrobial agents has been employed in polyolefins by incorporating hindered amine light stabilizers (HALSs) as N-halamine precursor (Chen and Sun, 2005a, 2005b) (Fig. 8.2
). HALSs are one of the most important light/thermal stabilizing agents of polymeric materials (Table 8.3
).
